\pard\widctlpar\qj\tx720\fs52 T\fs24 elling an employee that his or her job is being eliminated is, perhaps, one of the most difficult challenges a manager or supervisor may encounter. It is doubly hard for the affected employee to understand this action when they have no control over the decision. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf1\f2\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\tx720\cf0\f0 This guide has been created to assist managers and supervisors in working through the layoff process with dignity and respect for both the employee who is leaving, and for the employees remaining in the department. We have researched best practices from a variety of organizations and other sources and have compiled the following information that we hope you will find helpful in managing these changes in your department. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf1\f2\par
\f0\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\tx720\cf0\tab\fs114\par

\pard\widctlpar\b\fs32 Layoff and/or Restructure Process Steps\par
\b0\fs22\par
There are a number of considerations that must be met on any layoff/ restructure process.\~ The following are the essential steps: \par
\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720 Create a layoff justification document that outlines the \lquote talking points\rquote  regarding the rationale behind this decision (see page 5).\~ This document is used in a number of ways \endash  HRS will use it to provide the appropriate union with the essential information, information will also be incorporated in the talking points in letters to the employee(s), it will inform content for other communications with staff within the department and any other stakeholder(s) you will want to inform. \~\par

\pard\widctlpar\li720  \par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720 Complete the Incumbent Seniority List worksheet. HRS will need to review the worksheet to ensure that all Collective Bargaining Agreement provisions are met.\~ This list needs to be reviewed prior to communicating to employee(s).  \~ You can send this document along with your talking points to HRS for review.\~ \par

\pard\widctlpar\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720 Meet with an HRS consultant \endash  to talk through any questions, concerns, resources, issues etc., prior to implementing the communications.\~ This may help you to frame your approach and put together needed resources for the impacted staff.\~ \par

\pard\widctlpar\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720 Assess communication and change management issues that will impact your team.\~ The Stakeholder Analysis Worksheet and/or the Communication Plan at a Glance worksheet will help you think through who will be impacted by this layoff and help formulate your transition and communications plans.\~ These tools can be completed to the degree that you desire as it may help to identify issues that may have been overlooked.\~ For example,\~the work that is completed by this position to be laid-off will need to be transitioned. These tools will help plan what staff may want to know about that fact, training concerns, etc.\par

\pard\widctlpar\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720 Notify the employee(s) who has been targeted for layoff in a 1:1 meeting with a copy of the notification letter. Please note that you must provide a minimum of 30 days for most of our Collective Bargaining Agreements. \~The Best Practices document has several suggestions and a script on how to make this critical meeting effective.\~ Please read this section.\~ \b Very Important.\b0\~ \par

\pard\widctlpar\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720 Meet with the entire staff to provide the rationale and answer any questions.\~ This needs to be done as quickly as possible after your meeting with the impacted staff member(s).\~ Finally, it is important that you continually follow up with staff during and after the layoff period to make sure that any residual issues are addressed quickly.\~ It is not uncommon for layoffs to trigger fears that in turn engender behaviors that may not be helpful to the team.\par

\pard\widctlpar\f1\fs24\page\f0\fs48 Communication \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard\widctlpar\fs52 C\fs24 ommunication is key to a successful layoff process. If your department is facing the need to restructure your department\rquote s workforce, here are some important points to remember: \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\ul\par
\b Prior to the layoff notification(s) \ulnone\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj\ul\b0 Plan your communication early\ulnone  - Plan what you will tell your employees about possible layoffs.  Developing a formal communications document with a list of talking points will be helpful.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}\ul Communicate early and often\ulnone . Plan when you will tell your employees about possible layoffs. Keep them apprised of developments over time. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}\ul Communicate openly and honestly\ulnone . Employees can better plan for a worst-case scenario if they know the possibilities. \par

\pard\widctlpar\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\ul\b During the layoff notification process \ulnone\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj\tab\b0  See \ldblquote Preparing for and Conducting the Layoff Notification Meeting\rdblquote  (beginning on page 5) \par

\pard\widctlpar\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\ul\b After the layoff notification(s) \ulnone\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj\ul\b0 Continue communication with separating employee(s\ulnone ). See \ldblquote Preparing for and Conducting the Layoff Notification Meeting\rdblquote  (beginning on page 5). \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}\ul Communicate with the remaining staff. \ulnone Remaining employees may feel that they will be next to lose their jobs and some may feel guilty when colleagues have lost their jobs. \par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1800\qj Be honest about what you know and what you can share. This not only minimizes concern relating to employees\rquote  own job security but also diminishes the rumor mill. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Facilitate group closure by giving employees a chance to express their concerns publicly and hear directly from you about what has occurred. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Listen to how they feel and prepare to reassure them. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Inform them of changes in workload or assignments and discuss with them how the work will be covered. \par

\pard\widctlpar\par
\par
\fs48 Creating Your Talking Points \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\cf1\fs52 A\fs24  \i Talking Points\i0  document is a very helpful tool in developing communications for the various audiences that will be impacted by a layoff. This document is a concise distillation of the reasons why the layoff is needed.  It is important to use the \i Talking Points \i0 as a basis of all communications that will occur during the layoff process.\i   \i0 This assures that everyone has the same information, and that communications are consistent\cf0 .  Key components of the \i Talking Points\i0  document include: \par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720 The rationale for the layoff including a history of why the layoff is necessary.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}The vision and mission of the organization.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Efforts made to minimize the impact of job loss.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}The value of how this change will positively impact the university (see core values below.) \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Who will be impacted \endash  those targeted for layoff, coworkers, campus community and/or students, etc.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}The changes that are anticipated (to the degree that they are known at this point) \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}What will not change (to the degree that this is known at the time of the announcement) \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}The timing for changes (as much as this is known) \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Resources that will be implemented to support those who are experiencing a job loss.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Who to contact for more information (name, title, phone number, email address) \par

\pard\widctlpar\par
Once the above communication document is created, it is important to filter the content through The University\rquote s core values and ask yourself if it reflects a commitment to the following:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\fs20 Learning experiences of high quality designed to allow students to realize their full potential; \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Basic and applied research that contributes to knowledge and meets the needs of the State, region, nation, and world; \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Diversity and community among students, faculty, and staff; \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Affordable access to higher education for Montanans; \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Effective and efficient use of resources, providing full accountability for all funds; and \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Service to the citizens, communities, regions, business, industry, State, and world.\~\par

\pard\widctlpar\fs24\par
When ever possible, incorporate the above core values into the Talking Points communication plan.\par
\fs48\par
Preparing for and Conducting a Layoff Notification Meeting \par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj I\fs24 nforming employee they are losing their job is a difficult and stressful task for a manager or supervisor. For the interaction between the employee and the manager or supervisor to go smoothly as possible, careful preparation and planning are the most important elements. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf1\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\cf0 The objectives of the notification meeting are twofold:\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi720\qj  (1) To inform the employee that his/her job has been eliminated and that he or she is being separated, \b and\b0\par
(2) To do so in a respectful and dignified manner that keeps the person feeling positive about the University and begins the transition process in a positive way. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf1\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\ul\b Pre-Meeting Preparation \ulnone\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj\b0 Be familiar with the circumstances (e.g. budget cuts, department reorganization) leading to the elimination of the employee\rquote s position. Also, be familiar with the process that was followed, including how the decision was made in selecting who would be laid off. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Prepare a script as a guide. This will ensure that you convey all the necessary information to the employee. Practice and rehearse the message you will deliver and how you will deliver it without reading your script word for word. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Consider if the employee will leave immediately after being notified of the layoff or will continue to work through the period of notice. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Consider how you will handle the employee\rquote s workload and what you will tell the employee if you are asked. Will it be distributed among other employees? Will services be eliminated? \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Prepare some recommended actions for the employee to pursue. Provide names and telephone numbers.  In addition, refer to the following as resources that are available for them:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1800\qj Employee Assistance Program  for counseling \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}HRS Benefits Representative to learn about available benefits \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Recruitment Representative to learn about preferential rehire and re-employment opportunities \par

\pard\widctlpar\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Be aware that the separation process can be emotional for all parties; prepare for this. Because of the emotional context it is important to anticipate questions you could be asked and have the answers to those questions available. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj\cf1 Take the time necessary to make the proper arrangements for the notification meeting. \par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1800\qj Select a place where you can have privacy. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Select a time earlier in the day on a day that is not immediately prior to a weekend, holiday, or scheduled vacation for either the employee or manager/supervisor.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Consider the day in relationship to significant dates for the employee (e.g. family celebration, religious holiday, employee\rquote s birthday, etc.) \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Plan for uninterrupted time. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Allow enough time to complete the meeting without being rushed including time for the employee to ask questions. \par

\pard\widctlpar\li360\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Consider having an appropriate person (i.e. a department administrative assistant) who is not privy to the subject of the meeting notify the employee of the meeting. This will allow you to introduce the purpose of the meeting in a private, controlled manner without engaging with the employee before you are prepared to speak to them. \par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj\tab\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Depending on your knowledge of the employee it may be advisable to have an EAP Counselor or a Human Resources Director be on-call or attend the meeting if needed. Discuss with them any possible problems you feel could occur or any concerns you may have.  In addition, you may also wish to consult with the UM\rquote s Public Safety department if you feel there is a possibility of a violent reaction. \par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj\tab\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Arrange for another manager to be with you during the meeting. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Assess the impact of the employee\rquote s departure on co-workers and clients. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Seek appropriate coaching from Human Resources Consultants and/or Faculty Staff Assistance Program Counselors. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\ul\par
\par
\b The Notification Meeting \par
\ulnone\par
\b0 Employee notifications should be conducted in person. Typically, the employee\rquote s immediate supervisor or the department manager conducts the notification meeting. This would \ul\b not\ulnone\b0  be a good time to have someone with whom the employee has never spoken conduct the meeting. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\cf1\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Don\rquote t engage in small talk, get to the point. Deliver the message directly but compassionately and allow the employee time to read the written notice of layoff you will give them during this meeting. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj\cf1 Stay with your script and remain calm. Straightforward, clear explanations are important. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj\cf1 Give the employee some background explaining why this decision is necessary. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Do not make comments, even if well intended, that could compromise the decision. Stay away from discussions that could confuse the primary message. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Be sensitive to the employee\rquote s situation, but also be direct and firm. Make sure that the employee knows the decision is final and is non-negotiable. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj\cf1 Don\rquote t blame others for the actions being taken. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Don\rquote t become defensive, argumentative or confrontational. It is best not to critique the decision that has been made. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Be sensitive to the employee\rquote s response. Hearing the employee does not mean you agree with him/her. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Tell the employee how much you appreciate the work they have done and recognize his/her contributions. \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj\cf0\f3\lang1024\'b7\tab\cf1\b\f0\lang1033 Offer support and encouragement; treat the employee in a dignified manner. \par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj\b0 Encourage the employee to contact the resources available (e.g. Employee Assistance Program, Benefits, Employment, etc.). \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Be available in the next few days to meet with the employee if he or she has additional questions. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Understand and appreciate the employee\rquote s position. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Focus the employee on the next steps in his/her future. \par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li360\qj Listen carefully and, after the meeting, document anything that could lead to a potential problem. Consult with Human Resources and/or Faculty Staff Assistance Program, if appropriate. \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\cf1\ul\b\page Problems that May Occur in the Meeting \par
\ulnone\b0\par
The employee may: \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\qj Become resistant, defensive and/or threatening want to plead his/her case, or bargain for another opportunity.\cf1\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}\cf0 Want to speak with a \ldblquote decision-maker\rdblquote .\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Ask \ldblquote why me?\rdblquote  questions.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Threaten a lawsuit or other formal action such as a retaliation complaint\cf1\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}\cf0 May get personally upset with the manager or supervisor\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Try to make the issue personal or about performance \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Argue about a person being retained who they believe is less capable, has less seniority, etc.\cf1\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}\cf0 List the repercussions cascading from the job loss.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Break down emotionally. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Go into shock and not accept what is happening.\par

\pard\widctlpar\li720\cf1\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\ul\b How to Deal with Emotional Reactions\par
\ulnone\b0 Stay in control of the meeting and your emotions at all times. Be familiar with, and comment on, how the decision was made.  Be supportive and offer positive suggestions where appropriate.  \par

\pard\widctlpar\li360\cf0\par
Be prepared for the following reactions:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1080 If crying occurs:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1440 Offer tissues\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Permit the employee the time to be alone to cry, if needed.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Be supportive, but refrain from touching the employee.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Be patient.\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1080 If anger occurs:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1440 Listen.  Anger is a normal response.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Respond to verbal attacks assertively.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Remain calm.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Do not discuss employee performance issues.\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1080 If silence occurs:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1440\tx1800\tx1980 Acknowledge the employee\rquote s feelings.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Allow the employee to discuss feelings.  Be empathetic.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Ask open-ended questions to determine that the employee understands the layoff message.\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1080\tx1800 If denial occurs:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1440\tx1800 Repeat or rephrase statements.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Ask open-ended questions to determine whether the employee understands the layoff message.\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1080\tx1800 If threats occur:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1440\tx1800 Ask the employee if he or she understands the seriousness of his or her words.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Suggest a brief cool down period, and then reconvene.\par

\pard\widctlpar\cf1\b\par
\b0\par
\par
\ul\b Things to Do After the Meeting\par
\ulnone\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720\b0 Conduct a follow-up meeting with the employee to see how he/she is coping and provide any information you were not able to provide in the notification meeting. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}If the employee is working until his/her separation date, you should supervise this employee just as you would any other employee. \par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Be aware of the employee\rquote s emotional state. If you have concerns, notify your resources.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Observe what\rquote s going on in the office between the separating employee and the remaining employees. (e.g., are the remaining employees being respectful and supportive or systematically excluding this person? How is the telephone being answered when this person is not around?).\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Notify Human Resources of any critical issues. \par

