\cf0\fs48 Follow-up with Remaining Employees\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\cf1\fs24\par
With discretion, inform the remaining employees about the action(s) that have taken place. Understand that people have lost friends and may have their own anxieties. Get people refocused quickly on any restructuring, reassignment of work or other changes.\par
\par
Discuss workload and/or support concerns and needs. Focus on the positives.\par
\par
Thank employees for their continued support but make no promises or guarantees about the future.\par
\par
Be accessible to your employees for any issues or concerns they may have about the changes.\par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\par
Above all, be tactful, direct and clear in explaining the circumstances that led up to the decision, the decision-making process, and the changes within the organization.  Offer employees the opportunity to ask questions.\par
\f1\page\f0\fs48 Sample Dialogue with the Employee \par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\cf1\fs44\par
T\fs24 he following information may assist in planning a script for the layoff notification meeting as well as preparing the manager or supervisor for various reactions from the employee. \par

\pard\widctlpar\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-1080\li1080 [Manager to employee] \par

\pard\widctlpar\tab\ul 1. Greet the employee. \ulnone\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\f4 Manager: Hello, _______. Thank you for meeting with me. \par

\pard\widctlpar\f0\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-720\li1080\qj\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-1080\li1080\qj\f4 Manager: I\rquote ve called this meeting because I must, unfortunately, inform you that your position has been eliminated. We do not have another position to offer you. This means you are being laid off. Here is your official Notice of Layoff. \par
. \par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-720\li1080\qj\f0 2. \ul Notification \ulnone (speak slowly and calmly) \par

\pard\widctlpar\li1080\ri1440\qj\par
(Give letter to employee and pause to allow the employee time to read the notice and process the information).\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-1080\li1080\qj\f4 Manager: As you may know, we are in a time of (budget cutbacks, reorganization, etc.) Although, we\rquote ve done everything possible to minimize the impact of these __________ on our department, we still need to implement some very difficult decisions.  I\rquote d like you to know that this action is not easily taken and only after long and careful review of many options. It is a final decision. \par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-720\li1080\qj\f0\par

\pard\widctlpar\qc\b (Pause for a few seconds) \par
\par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\qj\b0 Manager: I know this is difficult news. Is everything I\rquote ve said clear to you? Do you have any questions? \par

\pard\widctlpar\cf0\f2\par
\f0\par
\par
The employee will, typically, lead the conversation at this point. Answer questions honestly and appropriately. You should expect reactions anywhere in the range of emotional behavior to logical, strictly business related behavior.\par
\par
\par
\par
\ul\b Appropriate Response to Emotional Reactions \par
\ulnone\b0\par
In addition to physical reactions such as crying, anger and non-acceptance, emotional   responses may also include the \ldblquote why\rdblquote  questions. \ldblquote Why me?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Why not another employee?\rdblquote  \ldblquote Why did you make this decision?\rdblquote  Other questions may include:\par
\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li720 Who made this decision?\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Who can I talk with to get this decision reversed?\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Are there any other jobs available for me?\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Can I keep my job if I take a pay cut or reduce my time?\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Who else is being released?\par

\pard\widctlpar\par
Listen carefully and make eye contact with the employee. Assess the employee\rquote s emotional state and/or behavior to see if he/she might be a threat to himself/herself or others. If so, call your resources for assistance. Otherwise, answer those questions that are appropriate to answer. Do not allow the employee to continue too long.\par
\par
Show empathy for the employee but avoid trite statements or platitudes such as: \par
\par
\trowd\trgaph108\trleft1939\trrh310\trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\cellx6503 
\pard\intbl\widctlpar\ldblquote It\rquote s not the end of the world.\rdblquote  \cell\row\trowd\trgaph108\trleft1939\trrh310\trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\cellx6503 
\pard\intbl\widctlpar\ldblquote Consider this a blessing in disguise.\rdblquote  \cell\row\trowd\trgaph108\trleft1939\trrh310\trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\cellx6503 
\pard\intbl\widctlpar\ldblquote The glass isn\rquote t half empty, it\rquote s half full.\rdblquote  \cell\row\trowd\trgaph108\trleft1939\trrh310\trpaddl108\trpaddr108\trpaddfl3\trpaddfr3
\cellx6503 
\pard\intbl\widctlpar\ldblquote It\rquote s just a job.\rdblquote  \cell\row 
\pard\widctlpar\par
Manager: \tab Is there someone I can call for you? \par
\f1\par
\f0 While you may wish to continue with the meeting, consider what might be best for the employee and whether he/she will hear any further information you may deliver at this time. In most cases, you should take the time to deal with the emotional reactions and responses of the employee before turning to any \ldblquote housekeeping\rdblquote  matters you need to deal with. \par
\b Or \b0\tab\tab Would you like to take a brief break before we continue? \par
\par

\pard\widctlpar\fi-1440\li1440\b Or\b0  \tab Would you like to leave for the rest of the day and we can continue this discussion tomorrow?\par

\pard\widctlpar\par
In many instances, the employee may move directly to the facts relating to the layoff. This allows the manager to begin discussion of the \ldblquote housekeeping\rdblquote  matters. \par
\par
\b Housekeeping Matters \par
\b0 Manager: At this point, I need to discuss with you how you will leave the department and the resources and assistance the University makes available to you. \par
\par
\par
This transition statement will reinforce that the action being taken is final and will begin moving the employee forward in that direction. Again, make eye contact with the employee and speak calmly. \par
\par
\par
\par
Given the staff person will be working after the notification meeting, it will be important to discuss the following:\par
\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\widctlpar\fi-360\li1080 Confirm last date of work.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Encourage the staff member to make an appointment with Human Resource Services to review transition resources such as:\par

\pard{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf10\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\hyphpar0\widctlpar\fi-360\li1800\f6 Hiring Preference Procedures.\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Resume Service/Effective Interviewing\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Time Off To Attend Interviews\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}Health Benefits\par
{\pntext\f10\'B7\tab}How to Apply for Unemployment Benefits\par

\pard\widctlpar\f0\par
In addition, whenever possible, make efforts to complete recognition events, going away parties, etc.  Obtain permission from the affected staff members before scheduling an event.   \par
\par
